{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-simple-way-to-integrate-dash-with-ldap-4d5d059ee3a6", "time": 1683016356.842864, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-simple-way-to-integrate-dash-with-ldap-4d5d059ee3a6/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Add AD authentication to your Dash app | by Erik Petrovski | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Add AD authentication to your Dash app", "description": "In most organizations, login credentials are managed by a directory service like Active Directory. If you manage to integrate Dash with your organization\u2019s directory service then users can simply log\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://pypi.org/project/dash/", "anchor_text": "Dash", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lightweight_Directory_Access_Protocol", "anchor_text": "LDAP", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://pypi.org/project/Flask/", "anchor_text": "Flask", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://github.com/epetrovski/dash_ldap", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://pypi.org/project/pipenv/", "anchor_text": "Pipenv", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/epetrovski/dash_ldap/blob/main/app.py", "anchor_text": "app.py", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://help.ubuntu.com/community/EnvironmentVariables", "anchor_text": "environment variable", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "http://127.0.0.1:8000", "anchor_text": "http://127.0.0.1:8000", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://flask-simpleldap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/", "anchor_text": "flask-simpleldap", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://gunicorn.org/", "anchor_text": "gunicorn", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["In most organizations, login credentials are managed by a directory service like Active Directory. If you manage to integrate Dash with your organization\u2019s directory service then users can simply log in to your Dash app with their existing credentials. A common way of doing this is by way of LDAP (an open protocol for speaking with directory services like Active Directory) and Flask (a lightweight web application framework). In this post, I\u2019ll demonstrate how to integrate LDAP and FLASK with Dash in Python in \u2014 as far as I know \u2014 the simplest way possible.", "Before getting into any code, you need to have LDAP already up and running. This is a major step that\u2019s out of the scope of this article which only focuses on the Python side of things. If you need AD integration however, I\u2019m assuming that you work in a pretty large organization with its own IT-department and hopefully that department is (1) not you and (2) willing to help!", "Assuming LDAP is up and running, go ahead and clone the example code from GitHub by running:", "We also need a few libraries to build a Dash app and make it work with LDAP \u2014 four in total. If you already use Pipenv, just run the following in a terminal inside the cloned dash_ldap directory to get a full working virtual environment with dependencies installed:", "If you don\u2019t want to mess with Pipenv, just install the dependencies you need with:", "All the code you need is in app.py. Let\u2019s go through it line by line.", "The first trick is to make Dash run inside a Flask app that serves your Dash app to the outside world. This is done by passing a Flask object to the Dash app\u2019s server argument at initialization like so:", "We then define a Dash app for purpose of example. This app is just a simple placeholder but don\u2019t worry, when you build your own app with advanced callbacks etc., it won\u2019t require any changes to the LDAP integration setup.", "You\u2019ll now need to configure Flask for LDAP by updating Flask\u2019s configuration dictionary. The details below is just a placeholder as your credentials will depend on your company\u2019s LDAP setup \u2014 again, ask IT!", "You may have noticed that I\u2019ve taken the liberty and added the LDAP_PASSWORD with an os.getenv(). I\u2019m assuming that you would never store a password in code but use something like an environment variable instead.", "Very importantly, now we need to protect all of Dash\u2019s view functions that have been registered with Flask with an authentication requirement by wrapping them with LDAP(app.server).basic_auth_required():", "Finally, we may want a way to run the Flask app quickly for testing purposes. Usually we would use app.run() but since the app is served on a Flask server, we use app.run_server():", "You can confirm that the AD integration is working by running:", "Now navigate to http://127.0.0.1:8000 and you should see a login prompt. Punch in your credentials and you should see the \u2018Hello world!\u2019 frontpage.", "Now that you\u2019re pleased with having everything running smoothly, please remember that a crucial part to making this all work is the flask-simpleldap package. It\u2019s one of those great Python packages that just works and solves a very unglamorous but crucial IT need.", "If you\u2019re running your Dash app in production, you should be running the app on a production grade http server like gunicorn. You already have this installed, so just run:", "This works because in app.py, I\u2019ve defined:", "There you go, a login protected Dash app that integrates with a directory service and is fit for production!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F4d5d059ee3a6&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-simple-way-to-integrate-dash-with-ldap-4d5d059ee3a6&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, 